</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[946,1042,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[946,1042,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished from other American species of 
<taxonomicName box="[397,512,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[397,512,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Mesovelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the mesofemur ventrally without a row of spinules; the posterior margin of abdominal tergum VIII with a weak notch; abdominal pleuron VIII with an anterodorsal tubercle (
<figureCitation box="[1329,1398,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1903,1925]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,373,1881]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mesovelia tuberculata sp. nov. (A) male, holotype, dorsal view; (B) male, holotype, ventral view; (C) male, holotype, lateral view; (D) female, paratype, dorsal view; (E) female, paratype, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254990/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C); abdominal sternum VI with the posteromedian projection rounded, with a fringe of black spinules (
<figureCitation box="[1283,1348,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1903,1925]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,373,1881]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mesovelia tuberculata sp. nov. (A) male, holotype, dorsal view; (B) male, holotype, ventral view; (C) male, holotype, lateral view; (D) female, paratype, dorsal view; (E) female, paratype, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254990/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
B); and the paramere with margins converging and apex single (
<figureCitation box="[779,845,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1936,1958]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1485,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,1485,1914]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Parameres. (A) M. amoena Uhler [modified from Spangler (1990)]; (B) M. mulsanti White [modified from Moreira et al. (2008)]; (C) M. zeteki Harris &amp; Drake; (D) M. tuberculata sp. nov.." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254992/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
D).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,680]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">
The new species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[590,691,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zeteki">
<emphasis box="[590,691,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">M. zeteki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because males of both do not have spinules on the mesofemur and on abdominal sternum VII, but display a fringe of spinules on abdominal sternum VI. These two species can be distinguished because males of 
<taxonomicName box="[504,669,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[504,669,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">M. tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[676,765,404,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[676,765,404,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are shorter, from 
<quantity box="[964,1119,404,429]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" unit="mm" value="1.65" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.5">1.5 to 1.8 mm</quantity>
long, and have the posterior margin of abdominal tergum VIII with a weak notch, abdominal pleuron VIII with an anterodorsal tubercle (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1903,1925]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,373,1881]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mesovelia tuberculata sp. nov. (A) male, holotype, dorsal view; (B) male, holotype, ventral view; (C) male, holotype, lateral view; (D) female, paratype, dorsal view; (E) female, paratype, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254990/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C), abdominal sternum VI with the posteromedian projection rounded (
<figureCitation box="[974,1039,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1903,1925]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,373,1881]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mesovelia tuberculata sp. nov. (A) male, holotype, dorsal view; (B) male, holotype, ventral view; (C) male, holotype, lateral view; (D) female, paratype, dorsal view; (E) female, paratype, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254990/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
B), and the paramere with margins converging and apex single (
<figureCitation box="[478,546,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1936,1958]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1485,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,1485,1914]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Parameres. (A) M. amoena Uhler [modified from Spangler (1990)]; (B) M. mulsanti White [modified from Moreira et al. (2008)]; (C) M. zeteki Harris &amp; Drake; (D) M. tuberculata sp. nov.." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254992/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
D). In contrast, males of 
<taxonomicName box="[831,934,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zeteki">
<emphasis box="[831,934,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">M. zeteki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are about 
<quantity box="[1055,1142,512,536]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
long and have abdominal tergum VIII with the posterior margin straight, abdominal pleuron VIII without a tubercle (
<figureCitation box="[1204,1274,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1414,1436]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1391]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1392]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mesovelia zeteki Harris &amp; Drake, holotype, male. (A) dorsal view; (B) ventral view; (C) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254991/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C), abdominal sternum VI with the central projection of the posterior margin acute (
<figureCitation box="[961,1032,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1414,1436]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1391]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1392]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mesovelia zeteki Harris &amp; Drake, holotype, male. (A) dorsal view; (B) ventral view; (C) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254991/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
B), and the paramere with margins diverging and apex bifid (
<figureCitation box="[440,507,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1936,1958]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1485,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,1485,1914]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Parameres. (A) M. amoena Uhler [modified from Spangler (1990)]; (B) M. mulsanti White [modified from Moreira et al. (2008)]; (C) M. zeteki Harris &amp; Drake; (D) M. tuberculata sp. nov.." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254992/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1368,655,680]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,680]" box="[199,1368,655,680]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,655,680]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName box="[575,703,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis box="[575,703,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, refers to the tubercle on anterodorsal area of pleuron VIII.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
